\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{Discrimination between moth and bat call series}{13}{section*.24}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces  Classification of moth and bat calls. (A) Spike train matching for moth call series (left column) and extended moth call series (right column) with the pairing of all moth call series (Call ID) shown on the both axes. Number of matched spike trains is color coded. Each row is based on a different temporal resolution used in the computation of the VanRossum spike train distance (1~ms, 10~ms and 1000~ms) (B)Classification heatmaps for call series, extended call series and Poison spiking model (top to bottom). The percentage of correct classifications is color coded and plotted over spike train duration and different temporal resolutions of the VanRossum spike train distance (tau values). The vertical dashed black lines indicate spike train duration where the classification performance is more than 50~\% and more than 80~\%. (C) Moth vs Bat call series. Percentage of moth classification (color coded) depending on spike train duration and the temporal resolution of the VanRossum spike distance (tau values). The red line in each heatmap separates moth (M) from bat (B) call IDs. (D) Heatmap of the sensitivity index d-prime (color coded) for the discrimination task between moth and bat call series depending on spike train duration and the temporal resolution of the VanRossum spike distance (tau values). }}{15}{figure.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:03}{{3}{15}{Classification of moth and bat calls. (A) Spike train matching for moth call series (left column) and extended moth call series (right column) with the pairing of all moth call series (Call ID) shown on the both axes. Number of matched spike trains is color coded. Each row is based on a different temporal resolution used in the computation of the VanRossum spike train distance (1~ms, 10~ms and 1000~ms) (B)Classification heatmaps for call series, extended call series and Poison spiking model (top to bottom). The percentage of correct classifications is color coded and plotted over spike train duration and different temporal resolutions of the VanRossum spike train distance (tau values). The vertical dashed black lines indicate spike train duration where the classification performance is more than 50~\% and more than 80~\%. (C) Moth vs Bat call series. Percentage of moth classification (color coded) depending on spike train duration and the temporal resolution of the VanRossum spike distance (tau values). The red line in each heatmap separates moth (M) from bat (B) call IDs. (D) Heatmap of the sensitivity index d-prime (color coded) for the discrimination task between moth and bat call series depending on spike train duration and the temporal resolution of the VanRossum spike distance (tau values)}{figure.3}{}}
